segments.text: So then in 1930 you went to the Air Corps Technical School and you stayed there for a year?
No, it was less than that.
I think it was only about six months.
Okay, okay.
And what did you learn at the technical school?
Armament.
This is the munitions, guns, bombs, sights.
Everyone back then was supposed to have a specialty, but he wasn't required to stay in it as they are now.
Mm-hmm.
I didn't actually get back into my specialty in the war until the war came.
Mm-hmm.
And I wish I hadn't then, but go ahead.
And then in 1931, you were transferred to Hawaii?
Something like that.
Yeah.
Okay, you were assigned to Hawaii.
To a bomb squadron, a tactical unit.
Mm-hmm.
And how long were you there?
Three years.
And you were, what were you doing, training?
I was the squadron engineering officer.
Generally speaking, the whole deal was a training deal.
Sure.
You were training for war, of course.
You didn't see any war.
I'll illustrate.
When I first
accepted my regular commission.
I had a commission leave and went home.

And my father took me on a roundabout that he was going on, but introduced me to a man that he knew who was a retired Army colonel who'd spent 30 years in the service, retired and was an office manager for a firm.
So we sat and talked about it, and I said, I was by no means sure that I wanted to stay in the service, as I told you.
And I said,
The purpose of the military is to have a war, and I don't see any prospect of a war.
And he said, son, I was in the service 30 years, and from time to time things looked mighty bleak.
It looked like we'd never have another war, but I was in three of them.
Well, he didn't think it was funny.
I did.
I still do.
Things looked mighty bleak.
That is sort of like that.
We were training, and as it turned out, we didn't realize how well we were trained.
People who had to accept much, much higher responsibilities as a rule turned out pretty well.
So you were in Hawaii then, training from 1932 to 1935.
At this time, Japan
was moved in 1931, moved against Manchuria, and were you out there or the people out in Hawaii worried about Japanese expansion at this time?
Do you remember if that was a concern then?
Yes, it wasn't a great concern of a second lieutenant.
Yeah.
But I remember it.
In fact, yes, I remember it, and I remember

Even more, a couple of incidents of a Japanese that I've happened to run into, well, in the Big Island of Maui, for example, one night, a goddamn near riot, anyway, the fierce hatred between the Japanese and Chinese.
You see, another thing about it, which I might add, for whatever it's worth, the islands were
largely populated by Japanese, Chinese.
And of course, the originals, but no one there trusted the Japanese because of this feeling that this thing that none of us really believed would happen.
I certainly didn't.
I didn't really think it would happen, but nobody trusted them.
Now, this was unfair.
because as you know the history of the Japanese units and the war and what happened, it was quite unfair.
And the internment on them was quite unfair.
But it was part of the deal.
Back in the United States at this time, we had of course the Great Depression.
Did the Great Depression have any impact on the military?
Not much.
Don't get me wrong, I knew about it.
My sister, for example, and her husband suffered under it quite a bit.
They came out of it, but the props fell out from under them.
But it didn't affect us much.
Oh, to be sure, there were certain things, the strictures on the military, we couldn't
We had no money to pick up fuel.
We had to go where the fuel was and we couldn't go, that sort of thing.
And oh hell, when I went to Hawaii, that was at the time the banks were frozen.
Sure.
And I had no money to go on, and when I was ordered to go, I had to go.
There was a tailor that I bought uniforms from, and I was bitching about this.
I was going to have to make it some way.
And he said, how much money you need?
And I told him about what I thought it'd take to get to California.
And he reached under a pile of cloth and got the money and gave it to me, and lent it to me.
He had been warned that this was going to happen.
He'd gone over to the bank and drawn out a roll, a bill that big.
And of course, we were ordered to do things and didn't have any per diem.
These were, as it were, at our own expense.
Honestly, that wasn't a handicap compared to what was going on in the civilian economy.
I see.
Not at all.
I was told, for example, at one time I had to cut my, I couldn't fly more than a certain number of hours a year.
Sure.
So I went to a senior officer and I said, look, I'm going to fly more than that because I'm ordered to.
And he said, don't bother with it.
Just keep track.
Just keep your copies of your orders.
And when I ran up against the deadline of the number of hours, nobody said a word.
I went ahead and flew as ordered.
Presumably, somebody else didn't fly to that limit.
I don't know.
But these things are picky.
The Depression didn't really hurt.
What it did do, however, of course, was fund
some elegant construction, Randolph, Hamilton Field, beautiful places, and Maxwell, which couldn't possibly have been built except for that money.
I want to point out that the country sure got a lot for that money, the construction quality.
those projects were just simply unbelievable compared to what you get nowadays for 15 times the amount of money, but let's drop it.
Now one aspect about the military during the 1930s was that advancement was real slow.
Yeah.
Did that
Did that have any impact on you?
I mean, did it make you- Bother me a bit.
Didn't bother you?
No.
You see, the whole thing was on a seniority basis.
And I reckoned that if I was lucky, that I'd retire as a major.
If I wasn't, I'd retire as a captain.
I didn't worry about that.
The hierarchy, the structure,

occasionally was bothersome because you'd get some old fud that wasn't worth a goddamn who nevertheless held the rank to give orders but almost invariably some way would be found to get this man out of the way and go ahead about your business.
I could illustrate that but there's no point in it.
Okay, 1935 you left Hawaii and you went
As a flying instructor, you were assigned as a flying instructor to the Air Corps Advanced Flying School, and you were there for the next six years from 1935 to 1941.
Well, what happened was this.
The war in Europe got people realizing that our forces were not big enough, and particularly the Air Force wasn't.
I was ordered away.
As a matter of fact, I was ordered to the engineering school at Wright-Patt.
That's an advanced
engineering school for the Air Corps, a pretty high level aeronautical engineering deal.

And I was on my way to Wright-Patt, just going by way of New York to look at a couple of shows, and was having breakfast in the club on my way to Wright-Patt to find a place to live, when a classmate of mine came in the club, had breakfast, sat down, and said,
Are you going?
I told him, ordered up.
He said, well, no, you're not.
Back then, the New York Times used to publish orders.
It was so small that it was news.
So he backed pages of the New York Times, Lieutenant Kennedy orders, and so forth, canceled.
And I had been ordered up there once before.
And the commander, Kelly, blocked those.
Then this came up because we had this expansion.
That's how it happened that I was there so long.
The first part of that duty was finally- So it was down at Kelly.
Yes.
And so I stayed there.
Yeah.
And I went to England before we were in the war while I was still assigned to Kelly.
But the first part of that duty was absolutely delightful.
It really was.
no comparison to it in anything I served in.
Why?
Why do you say that?
Well, because you were instructing in a system which is long, long since outmoded.
You got assigned a group of students to yourself, and you could work with them for their individual characteristics, what they were.
you were given a lot of latitude in your duty.
And furthermore, every four months a class graduated, and we'd have about two weeks when we didn't have a class there.
And the line was full of airplanes, and you could go get one and go any goddamn place you wanted to.
And I did.
Also, we had a hunting and fishing camp down in Mount Agorda.
In the first part of it, we frequently didn't fly in the afternoons.
And our night flying was set aside so that you knew when that was.
And you could take off at noon and go down there and fish or hunt and come back at night.
And it was a very pleasant life.
We were congenial.
All the guys that were doing this kind of work liked it.
If they didn't,
He didn't have to do it, and it was far and away the most pleasant service I ever had.
As time went on and the war came on in Europe, it was not that much fun because it was a night and day job all the time.
I'm not criticizing it because it was still good work, but you had to formalize it.
This is the nature of things.
You had to put in a production line in order to get it all done.
And you couldn't deal with the individuals as you could before.
You could as best you could, but it wasn't the same.
Also, I was taking out a good deal and a lot of part of it to do other work, field location boards and that sort of thing.
How good was the training that you gave the pilot cadets?
I don't think there were any better pilots in the world than what we had during that time.
Mind you, there are no better pilots in the world right now than the U.S. Air Force.
Possibly the Israelis.
They use the same system.
But man for man, they're probably about as good as we are.
They don't have as good an Air Force.
I didn't mean that.
No, but that, see that old system couldn't turn out the number you needed.
Right.
And I don't think there are any spots on the pilots.
We turned out back then, they were the best.
And we didn't just turn them out for the Air Force, we turned them out for the airlines too.
Yeah.
No, I don't have any, I don't have doubts about that.
I'm not being just prideful of my service.
I think this is an objective point of view.
I think we proved it.
And what type of training did you yourself offer?
Well, my, you mean additional being a flying instructor?
No, what, I mean, were you...
instructor for the bombers or for the fighters?
Most of the time I spent in the bomb section.
I was about to tell a story but it won't illustrate anything so I'll get off it.
Most of the time it was bombers.
We got the castoffs from the Tactical Air Force.
As the Tactical Air Force got through with an airplane, we got it.
So generally our airplanes were old, but they were pretty reliable.
I want to be explicit about this.
They weren't worth a goddamn as combat airplanes.
This was an oversight on the part of the Air Force that went way back.
We didn't get good combat airplanes until we were in combat.
But they were good airplanes.
For example,
I trained for a while with a thing called a B-18.
That was a two-engine bomb, a great big goddamn thing.
It was a good airplane.
It wasn't worth a damn as a combat airplane.
The first airplane that would have been in any way worthy as a combat airplane, we didn't even get it as a trainer, was a B-10.
And the B-17, as it came out originally, was a hell of a good airplane, one with a dam as a combat airplane.
I'm a bit prejudiced in this because, as I told you, my specialty was the combat mechanism of the airplane.
And that's the part that was so long overlooked.
And much of this had to be repaired in the stress of war.
But as flying machines and as pilots, there weren't anywhere in the world any better.
And we got foreign students.
I trained a number of foreign students when I was at Kelly.
Where were they from, England?
No, South America.
South America, okay.
Now during this time, during the mid-1930s,
According to Chenault's memoirs, have you ever read Way of the Fighter?
Who?
General Claire Chenault, have you ever read his memoirs?
I'm sorry I haven't, I knew him.

He stated that the Army Air Corps overlooked the potential of fighter airplanes and that there were a group of bomber generals who ran the show and those people thought that heavy bombers could never be attacked
and would always be able to withstand any kind of anti-aircraft fire, and therefore we didn't need fighters, and we usually trained people in bombers.
What did you think about the use of fighters versus bombers?
Chenault was dead right.
Improved it.
See, I'm not aware of the book.
I don't know why, but anyway, I haven't read it.
But I'm well aware of this particular contention on his part because I was there.
He left the service because he couldn't get anybody to listen.
He was absolutely right, and the war proved it.
The problem, the fundamental, the basic problem is still with us.
I don't want to wade into that.
The best man you can talk to about that is Bernie Schreiber.
What did you think of Chenault?
You said you knew him.
Look, he was an instructor at Brooks when I went through here.
And, oh Christ, that guy could fly better than anybody, but anybody except a few of his contemporaries were just as good.
I remember, just to illustrate, they had a competition about who could make the landing more accurately with a goddamn PT, primary trainer.
And Brooklyn, they named the field after him, Chenault, who the hell was the third one?
He's dead too, so it doesn't matter.
Anyway, they marked the place
just over the helm and the airplane had to come down just like this.
And so, you know what a campaign hat is?
We used to wear them, a big goddamn thing.
Chenault put his hat down there and the tailskid of the airplane was a marker.
Chenault came in and put his tailskid on his hat.
Gee whiz.
I remember, for example,
sitting by the stage house.
There was a stage house.
There's a thing straight up in Brooks Field, out in the field.
And then there was a crapper over here.
It was a pretty big one.
And we'd sit around there and fly from that place because it was more convenient than the hiring line.
But this morning the fog was in low and we were just sitting around there and here come three airplanes.
And I don't know which one of them was leading, but he had convinced the other three, the other two,
that they couldn't get between the crapper and the stage house, but they did.
They overlapped their wings and did.
That's the kind of people they were.
And Chenault, as you may know if you read his book, I'm sure he told you, he designed the fighter tactics that were used.
And he had a flying circus up there at Maxwell.
He had one at Kelly for that matter.
But what he was trying to tell these guys was the same thesis that I'm telling you, that goddamn airplanes weren't worth a crap for combat.
And they were great to fly.
See, the big bomber guys thought that they could fly over the flak, but damn it, anybody that knew anything about German munitions knew goddamn well they couldn't.
And the British tried to tell us that.
Of course, there was one point I want to make in which logic did prevail.
And I say this because I'm familiar with that too.
I flew an observation for a time.
This is a two-man airplane in which one guy does the observing and the other one doesn't.
And we realized in time that that could not survive.
And the mission, which observation had had, was scrubbed and went into fighters as reconnaissance.
That's what you call it now.

So it wasn't a total loss situation because the Air Corps people didn't have sense enough to realize that that thing that they'd been doing so long, which the Army thought was great, couldn't survive, and they didn't stay with it.
The painful part of it was getting all this munitions onto the airplane, which people wouldn't, goddammit, no matter what you said, they wouldn't design it onto the airplane.
I remember too well the time when a fighter guy would look to see whether or not the baggage compartment would carry a stick of
It's golf clubs, and it's B4 bag.
That's all he was interested in.
He didn't give a damn about the guns.
What you want to do and what you must do in a weapons system is start with what you're going to do with the goddamn thing.
That's all Chenault was trying to tell people.
And trying to tell them things that were perfectly obvious, but they wouldn't listen.
They still don't.
Why do you think they would not listen?
I can take it out of context and explain it very quickly.
They're bringing a battleship out of mothballs.
You know why?
The Navy loves battleships.
I don't want to talk about it anymore.
It's a highly complex subject.
This is the area
that I mentioned a while ago, where you have all kinds of forces, not headed bastards to deal with.
And if you want to come out with a project goal, you have to deal with all those things.
You can't get exasperated about them.
And these two men I mentioned were masters of it.
I mean, two Aggie generals that I mentioned are masters of it.
Ludeke and Shriver.
God almighty.

But I remember when Bernie, for example, was patting the halls in the Pentagon, trying to put over what he was trying to put over, trying to get the knotheads to go along with him, and he was just about to be shipped out to, I don't know whether he knew it or not, I think he did, but he prevailed.
That's what it takes.
Hell, let's get off that subject.
Okay, let's...
Did Chennault teach you how to fly?
Oh, no.
He was a stage commander, a check pilot.
Did I fly with him?
No, no.
I flew with the third guy.
He's here.
He lives out in the country.
Nick Carter.
I'll illustrate, and I never had to write a check with Chenault, so I never flew with him, but I knew him.
And you had to know people like that.
God damn it, he was a... Let me illustrate the methodology.
I had an instructor who was a hell of a nice guy.
As a matter of fact, he was from A&M.
But he fell out, and I had a series of them, and it happened at the time I was coming up for a check, I had a true horse's ass.
And so I went into this check ride, you know, God damn, am I gonna do something right or not, and fiddled around, and I was about to bust it.
The check ride is, you do things, you spin to a point, and they cut the gun on you, and you find a place to land, and all kinds of goddamn things, everything that you're supposed to know how to do.
So this guy I was riding a check with just gave me uncharted hell in the air, cut the gun.
There was no gospel system in it.
You had to holler at each other.
Well, I didn't lose my temper, but I did get angry.
And so he gave me a force landing, and I just cut the gun and walked it down, mad.
He says, for Christ's sake, why don't you do that all the time?
All he was really trying to do was to get me to be natural.
And he was being mean to do it.
And Chenault was that way.
But his mission, his objective was absolutely unchallengeable.
this would work with one fellow in the woodwork or not, I don't know.
I went through it myself later and my assessment was sometimes that's what you have to do and sometimes something else is what you have to do.
Sometimes you have to hold the guy's hand until he learns what he needs to know.
But I think, let's see,
The two men I mentioned are not familiar with Chenault because they're younger.
I don't know anyone alive now that can talk to you about Chenault in a really intimate way.
What about this Carter fellow?
What about Carter, this Carter fellow?
Well, Nick lives over on the other side of town.
He's a World War I pilot.
as Chenault was, of course.
He's way up in years.
He's even deafer than I am, and he's a naturally saturnine man.
If you wanted to call him, he'd talk to you, I guess, but I really wouldn't.
Unless you're going to do something on Chenault, specifically, I wouldn't recommend it.
I was wondering if you considered joining the American Volunteer Group
that Chenault organized in 1941.
I know that he came and talked to the President Roosevelt and Roosevelt allowed
military flyers to get out of the service to go on a one-year leave system and sign a contract with CAMCO, and I was wondering if you were contacted or thought about that.
Look, there's a considerable misconception about that.
A good many friends of mine did go, so I know where off I speak.
It was not that simple.
You were given to understand in no uncertain terms that if you bought in on that
you were through with the Air Corps.

Now it didn't turn out that way because by God when the time came the Air Corps needed those guys and needed them bad and as you know they all formed up in the Air Corps but that wasn't the way it was offered nor was it in Spain.
I wanted to go to Spain but you couldn't
You couldn't go as an observer.
You couldn't go anyway and still maintain.
And by that time, you see, I had a wife and child, and I just simply couldn't afford to.
There wasn't any way I could do that.
The men that I knew that went, with one exception, were all bachelors.
And the other one was a guy who was on his way out anyhow.
Did you know some of those people?
Who were some of those people that you knew when they became known as the Flying Tigers?
Oh, let me talk about just one.
He was at Kelly in pursuit, which is the fighters, and the third time he got lost on a cross country, he washed out and the reason he did was that
The guy that was running the section then had said, you know, this is how you do it.
This is, here's your map, and now this map in front of you.
And he went to some damn little place down like Wharton and couldn't find it.
Where was his map?
Well, he'd forgotten.
He'd put the map in his luggage compartment.
So he washed him out.
So he went to Spain on a $15,000 contract.
And that was pretty good back then.
In fact, it was damn good.
And this fellow that Clyde Rich, he's here retired now too, showed me a postcard he got from me saying, I go out on patrol frequently and think of you on each patrol.
Well, God Almighty, when he came home, he stopped off in Washington.
And of course they were very anxious to debrief him because we couldn't send anybody.
That was a very bad mistake.
This was proving ground for them.
I still regret it.
But we couldn't.
That's all there is to it.
Order of Roosevelt.
So they debriefed him, but he wouldn't talk until the guys on the air staff agreed that they would put him back on duty.
as a first lieutenant and send him to Kelly as an instructor.
So, they had to agree to that, and they did, and he showed up back at Kelly.
Well, when the Chennault thing came through, he took that and went.
What was his name?
Ajax Baumler.
A-J-B-A-U-M-L-E-R. Yeah, I've heard of him.
He's a soldier fortune type.
Anyway, he did a damn good job for Chanel.
When it came time to escort, for example, some of those hot shot guys didn't like to do that.
Ajax was there and he did his job and he ended up as an ace, of course, but he's all right.
He's the only man I ever turned in for a flag violation.
I didn't believe in that because I violated the rules myself and most everybody did, but this particular day,
By that time I had a section at Kelly, the far end, and I was responsible for the flight line on that end and my people, and I was taking off, there's an old railroad track going down there.
Anyway, here comes this guy, right square in my traffic, right down the railroad track, buzzing a train.
And I thought, God damn it.
He wasn't satisfied with that.
He came back head on into my traffic.
So I chased him and got his number and turns out it was Ajax.
And his excuse was he was teaching this guy how to attack a train.
I feel, well, he didn't hold it.
any ill will toward me, but I feel sort of guilty about it.
It's the only man I ever did turn in for a while.
That's the kind of man he was.
But when the time came in combat, he was a very cool, very good man.
That's one of them.
Another one was a man, one of my instructors, who was a good pilot, but so-so as an instructor.
I wasn't too sorry to lose him.
He was good.
I liked him.
What was his name?
Sandell.
He was killed.
Oh hell, I could name some more, but it doesn't matter.
Hell, Tex Hill's out here if you want to talk about that.
Did you know him?
I haven't met him.
I don't know him, no.
He doesn't know me either, I'm sure.
Did you know Johnny Allison?
Yes, very well.
What kind of man was he?
There's only one of them.
He's a cutter.
He's a good man.
You know his story, I suppose.
I know a little bit about him, but... Well, let me tell a story about him which may or may not be on the record.
I think it is, probably.
You remember Roosevelt said, give the Russians.
Okay, that's another story, and it isn't part of what you're looking at.
Anyway, some Russians came in, and so Arnold was chief then.
So he asked somebody to come up from Langley to demonstrate a P-40, I believe.
Oh yeah, yeah.
So Johnny came up and he really ran that thing out.

He knew he could get away with it, normally you can't, but he just brought it in right over their heads and made them duck and then spiraled it up and so forth and made it look like a good airplane, which it really wasn't much.
And so the Russians said, well if we're going to get that airplane we need somebody that can help us handle it.
So next thing you know Johnny was on his way to
Moscow.
And I guess I was on, anyway it converged about the time I was in England, on my way, whatever.
I don't remember my part of that particular deal.
But he was there then and they just put him in Durham's Vial.
He had a hotel room assigned, of course, and then he had a place out at the airport assigned, of course, where the airplanes were
And they just kept him under guard from the hotel, the airport, back to the hotel.
But he did a good job.
And you may know about his later.
He came back when the war was on.
Anyway, I mean for us.
Arnold called him in and told him he was to do this job, which I'm sure you're familiar with.
commander type operation.
No, I didn't know about this.
What was this now?
Johnny Olsen.
Yeah, when he came back from Russia, Arnold gave him what kind of job?
Well, it was not, the timing, there's a break in the timing, but we were in the war and they were going to do this operation behind the lines out there.
And Arnold called him in and told him that he was to
be in charge of the air part of it, and he could have whatever he needed.
But Johnny was pacing the halls of the goddamn Pentagon then.
Shit, I was gone.
Had to be because I didn't
See, when I was dealing with those people, they were in the munitions building.
I didn't know the Pentagon was there until after I got back after the war, but that's neither here nor there about the story on Johnny.
Nobody in the goddamn building knew that Arnold had told him this because it was so secret.
Johnny knew it, Arnold knew it, but when Johnny went to get something, he didn't know anything about it.
He had a hell of a job on his hands, but he prevailed.
And what was the commando operation?
Oh, hell, it was a robotic step scheme to drop people behind the lines, and it worked.
In France?
The main body of them were going in gliders.
You must know the story.
Anyway, it's in the record.
I don't have to go through all that with you.
And, of course, I only mention it because
Ellison is one of a kind.
He's a man that no matter what happens, no matter how bad it is, he doesn't lose his poise or sense of humor, which is better.
You might think of him as the renaissance man of the air age.
He's a little guy and that doesn't bother him a bit.
Most little guys it does.
Did you know Charlie Bond?
Charlie Bond?
Yeah, sure.
You're going to talk to him.
What did you think of Bond?
I knew him in peculiar circumstances.
He did a hell of a good job.
He was misplaced.
Bond is what they used to call a powder and shot man.
He's damn good.
He was in this, what you might call, sort of a quasi-diplomatic position and he worried about it and talked to me about it from time to time, but he's a damn good man.
No question about that.
But for his record, talk to him.
No.
Okay.
That didn't hurt him any.
What didn't hurt him?
The fact that he was in an assignment which didn't exactly suit his best talents.
Didn't hurt him a bit.
He's a good man.
Okay.
Now let's talk about when you went first to England.
Why did you go there?
To help the RAF?
No.
I went there because... Oh, shit.
There's no use going into the personality of this damn thing.
I went because I wanted to.
They had a war on them.
Yeah, I know they went to war in 1939 and there were some American fliers who joined the Canadian.
Yes, I know a lot of them.
Did you think about doing that?
Couldn't for the same reason.
I wouldn't have done it anyhow.
By that time I was too deeply committed to the Air Force.
I did consider it on the other situation, but the terms on which I had to do it were really out of the question.
My family responsibilities were such that I just simply couldn't do it.
Okay, now why did they send you to England?
To learn about how they were teaching gunners.
That was the mission.
And how long did you stay there?
Oh, I don't know.
I got back before the war started.
I think I got there 1st of July and got back the latter part of last of October, something like that.
1941, so it was after the Battle of Britain then.
Oh, yes.
They were still being bombed, but it wasn't anything serious.
How'd you get along with the British?
Well, I think it's fair to say that I got along with them just like most everybody, every other U.S. military person did.
